  "text": "Malate dehydrogenases (MDHs) often use malate or oxaloacetate as substrates to generate pyruvate and preferentially utilize NADP or NAD as cofactors. These differ in their subcellular localization among and within species [CITATION_1] . The function and regulation of MDH in animals are specifically associated with cell differentiation and proliferation, ontogenic development, hormonal control, and diseases [CITATION_2] . Stem protein spots 23 and 24 were identified as malate dehydrogenases (MDHs), which suggested that these might play a role in soybean NHR against B. maydis and provide new insights into their regulatory function beyond their classical role in basic metabolism.",
